# Repo Documentation Strategy

A guide for structuring documentation in AI-assisted projects. This covers two complementary systems:

1. **Layered Documentation** — persistent, human-readable docs that describe the project at every level of granularity
2. **Memory System** — a structured log of decisions, progress, and context that keeps AI tools grounded across sessions

Used together, these ensure that any AI tool can get up to speed quickly, and that context is never lost between sessions.

---

## Why This Matters for AI-Assisted Development

AI tools have no persistent memory between sessions. Without a structured documentation system:
- You re-explain context at the start of every session
- The AI makes decisions that conflict with earlier ones it can't see
- Progress and rationale are lost when a task is handed off or resumed

This documentation strategy solves that by making context **explicit, findable, and structured**.

---

## Part 1: Layered Documentation

Documentation exists at four levels. Each level serves a different audience and purpose.

| Level | File | Audience | Purpose |
|-------|------|----------|---------|
| **Project** | `AI_CONTEXT.md` | AI tools, new devs, stakeholders | Single source of truth for what this project is and how it works |
| **Module** | `AI_SUMMARY.md` (per module) | AI tools, module owners | What this module does, its boundaries, and how to work with it |
| **Task** | Workplan / task log | AI tools, developer working the task | Step-by-step context for a single piece of work |
| **Code** | Inline comments, docstrings | AI tools, code reviewers | Why a specific implementation decision was made |

---

### File Tree

```
project-root/
├── AI_CONTEXT.md               # Project-level overview (see contents below)
├── docs/
│   ├── architecture.md         # System design: components, data flow, infra
│   └── decisions.md            # Index of all ADRs (links to individual records)
└── src/
    ├── module1/
    │   └── AI_SUMMARY.md       # Module-level context (see contents below)
    └── module2/
        └── AI_SUMMARY.md
```

---

### `AI_CONTEXT.md` — What to Include

This is the first file an AI tool should read at the start of every session. Keep it concise and always up to date.

```markdown
# [Project Name] — AI Context

## What This Project Does
[1–2 sentences. What is it? Who uses it?]

## Tech Stack
[Language, framework, database, key libraries, deployment target]

## Architecture Overview
[Brief description of the major components and how they connect. Link to docs/architecture.md for detail.]

## Key Conventions
- [Naming conventions]
- [Folder structure rules]
- [State management approach]
- [API patterns]

## Where Things Live
| Concern | Location |
|---------|---------|
| API routes | `src/api/` |
| Business logic | `src/services/` |
| UI components | `src/components/` |
| Tests | `src/__tests__/` |

## Current Focus
[What is actively being worked on right now? What phase or milestone?]

## Do Not Touch
[Files, modules, or patterns that should not be modified without a team discussion]

## Last Updated
[Date and brief note on what changed]
```

---

### `AI_SUMMARY.md` — What to Include

One of these lives in each non-trivial module or feature directory. It gives an AI tool (or developer) enough context to work confidently inside the module without reading all the code.

```markdown
# [Module Name] — Summary

## Purpose
[What does this module do? What business problem does it solve?]

## Boundaries
- **Owns:** [What this module is responsible for]
- **Does not own:** [What it explicitly delegates elsewhere]
- **Depends on:** [Other modules or external services it calls]
- **Used by:** [Modules or entry points that depend on this one]

## Key Files
| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `index.ts` | Public API — only import from here |
| `service.ts` | Core business logic |
| `types.ts` | Shared types for this module |

## Patterns Used
[e.g. Repository pattern, event-driven updates, optimistic UI]

## Known Gotchas
[Anything non-obvious that has caused bugs or confusion before]

## Last Updated
[Date]
```

---

### `docs/architecture.md` — What to Include

A technical deep-dive into the system design. This is not a tutorial — it's a reference.

- System components and their responsibilities
- Data flow diagrams or descriptions
- Infrastructure and deployment topology
- External integrations and their contracts
- Scalability and performance considerations
- Security boundaries

---

### `docs/decisions.md` — What to Include

An index of all Architecture Decision Records (ADRs), not the ADRs themselves.

```markdown
# Architecture Decisions

| ADR | Title | Status | Date |
|-----|-------|--------|------|
| [ADR-001](./adrs/001-database-choice.md) | PostgreSQL over MongoDB | Accepted | 2024-01-10 |
| [ADR-002](./adrs/002-auth-strategy.md) | JWT with refresh tokens | Accepted | 2024-02-03 |
```

See `22-adr-documentation.md` in this library for the ADR template.

